President Biden has published an op-ed announcing new actions his administration is taking to implement the Bipartisan Safer Communities Act (BSCA) and reduce gun violence. The op-ed also honors the lives lost in Buffalo, New York, and Uvalde, Texas, due to gun violence. President Biden signed an Executive Order directing his Cabinet to submit reports summarizing their progress on BSCA within 60 days. The Department of Justice (DOJ) has denied over 160 firearms transactions due to enhanced background checks for individuals under 21. Prosecutions for unlicensed firearm dealing increased by 52% from FY 2021 to FY 2022. The Departments of Health and Human Services (HHS) and Education (ED) have provided over $1.5 billion to improve school safety, access to mental health services, and help those affected by gun violence. The President details 13 actions his Cabinet has taken or will take to maximize the benefits of the law, including keeping guns out of dangerous hands, utilizing mental health funding for trauma support, improving school safety, and expanding community violence interventions.